static, absolute, and fixed affect the document flow


//////////////
Relative
- not removed from document flow
- moves away form orginal position

Absolute
- removed from document flow
- positions itself to the nearest non-static container

Absolute and fixed are both removed from the document flow, fixed stays on the viewport while absolute remains in the same position and isn't permanently fixed on the viewport.

Sticky
-  not removed from document flow
- when scrolled on will stick to a certain position if it is in the code
   
   CSS prioritizes top and left
   Sticky doesn't prioritize anything

   higher z-index value = more forward it is
   (kinda like canva)
   the default z-index of elements in html is 0

   child containers automatically inherit the z-index of their parent container

   anything inside a container is the child of the container
   example: the child of body is everything inside it
   another example: the child of div is the box in it